Overview figure of raw data

Each figure is a scholarship of award competition, and it shows the ranks for female and male names as determined by the function gender in R. As a reminder lower ranks means that a student is ranked as better compared to the other applicants.

How does the median effect size compares to the unbiased 50% line, where there is no difference in ranking between female and male students?

These are the p-values of all the above effect sizes. What is the distribution of each test relative to the 0.05 significance cut-off line?

Finally, when we combine all effect sizes into one test, we can determine if there is a significant bias in effect sizes by determining if 0.5 is in the 95% confidence interval with a simple t-test:

One Sample t-test

data: summary.gender.rankings1718$effect.size.W t = -2, df = 10, p-value = 1 alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 0.5 95 percent confidence interval: 0.2614 Inf sample estimates: mean of x 0.3737

Conclusions

The good news is that this academic year, there is no evidence at all that we were biased in our evaluations. Thank you for your hard work in evaluating all the applications and awards.
